Q1. What is Concurrent Collections?
    You’re working on the backend of an app like Swiggy, and it’s peak dinner time. Orders are flying in.
    One person is adding biryani to their cart, another is placing an order for pizza, someone else is
    checking delivery updates, and another user is chatting with support — all happening at the same time.
    Behind the scenes, all of these features depend on shared data like carts, order queues, and chat systems.
    If the app doesn’t handle this properly, things can easily go wrong — items may disappear from carts,
    updates might get delayed, or even worse, the whole system might crash.

    That’s exactly why Java gives us concurrent collections. They’re built to let different parts of your app
    use the same data at the same time — safely, smoothly, and without stepping on each other’s toes.
Q1. What Are Concurrent Collections?
Standard definition:
    A concurrent collection is a special type of data structure in Java that’s built for multi-tasking.
    It lets different parts of your program safely use the same data at the same time —
    whether it's adding, removing, or updating.

    In simple words: it’s like a shared notebook that many people can use — and it stays clean, neat,
    and up-to-date, no matter how busy things get.

Q2. Why Do We Need Them?
    Without concurrent collections, managing shared data is like shouting across a noisy kitchen —
    orders get lost, overwritten, or mixed up.

    With concurrent collections:
        1. Everyone (threads) can work at the same time
        2. The data stays clean and correct
        3. Your app keeps running smoothly even under pressure

# Common Types of Concurrent Collections:
    Java has some concurrent collections that help manage shared data safely:

    1. ConcurrentHashMap:
        Think of this like a big kitchen whiteboard where multiple chefs can write or read notes at the same time — without any overlap.
        It allows safe reading and writing from many threads at once.

        Use it for:
            1. Storing active orders
            2. Tracking user sessions
            3. Real-time status updates

    2. CopyOnWriteArrayList:
        This is like a recipe book that makes a copy every time you update it. So one person can read the recipe
        while another updates it — safely.
        It’s best when there are many reads and very few writes.

       Use it for:
          1. Menus that rarely change
          2. Notification templates
          3. FAQs or help pages

    3. ConcurrentLinkedQueue:
        Imagine a perfectly organized queue in front of a billing counter. People can join or leave the line without pushing or cutting.
        This queue lets multiple threads add and remove items smoothly.

        Use it for:
          1. Message queues
          2. Chat systems
          3. Background tasks

# Key Points to Remember:
    1. Concurrent collections let different parts of your program use the same data at the same time — without breaking things.
    2. They're perfect for apps that are doing many things at once — like placing orders, updating carts, and chatting with support.
    3. These collections are built to keep shared data safe, clean, and correct in multi-threaded environments.
    4. ConcurrentHashMap is great for fast, shared lookups like active orders or session data.
    5. CopyOnWriteArrayList is useful when your data is read often but changed rarely, like menus or notifications.
    6. ConcurrentLinkedQueue works well when tasks need to move in and out smoothly, like a queue of messages or delivery updates.
    7. Without concurrent collections, shared data can easily get messed up — like too many chefs writing on the same board at once.

# Common Interview Questions & Answers:

    Q1: What are concurrent collections in Java?
    They are special data structures that allow multiple threads to read and write data safely at the same time.

    Q2: Why are concurrent collections important?
    Because in multi-threaded apps, many tasks happen at once. Concurrent collections help avoid problems like
    missing data or crashes by keeping everything organized.

    Q3: What is ConcurrentHashMap used for?
    It’s used when you want fast, thread-safe access to data — like storing active user sessions or live order info.

    Q4: When should you use CopyOnWriteArrayList?
    When your data is read more often than it’s written — for example, help pages or a list of FAQs.

    Q5: How does ConcurrentLinkedQueue help?
    It allows items to be added and removed smoothly — making it great for chat queues, task processing, or notifications.

